'''Edward Leroy "Ed" Koffenberger''' (c. 1926 <U+2013> September 21, 2014) was an American stand-out [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|basketball]] and [[Duke Blue Devils men's lacrosse|lacrosse]] player for the [[Duke University]] in 1945<U+2013>46 and 1946<U+2013>47. He is considered Duke's first "two-sport star"<ref name=GODUKE>{{Cite web| last = Duke Sports Information| title = Edward L. Koffenberger| work = GoDuke.com| publisher = [[Duke University]]| date = December 14, 2005| url = http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=220777| accessdate = September 16, 2010}}</ref> even though most of his accolades came from playing basketball. A native of [[Wilmington, Delaware]], Koffenberger is the only First Team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] basketball player from his home state when the [[Helms Foundation]] awarded him the distinction.<ref name=BOOK>{{Cite book| last = Gelbert| first = Doug| title = The Great Delaware Sports Book| publisher = Manatee Books| year = 1995| location = [[Montchanin, Delaware]]| pages = 115| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=EV557kOFNlcC&lpg=PA115&ots=XtnHgFuWfw&dq=Ed%20Koffenberger%20duke&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q=Ed%20Koffenberger%20duke&f=false| isbn = 0-9644427-0-1}}</ref> As a {{height|ft=6|in=2}} [[center (basketball)|center]], Koffenberger led the Blue Devils in scoring during both seasons he played for them, and during his [[senior (education)|senior]] season of 1946<U+2013>47, he led the [[Southern Conference]] in both scoring and rebounding.<ref name=BOOK/> He was a two-time All-American and two-time All-Conference selection in basketball, and in lacrosse he was a one-time All-American for his intimidating defensive presence.<ref name=GODUKE/> In 54 career basketball games he scored 733&nbsp;points, including a then-Duke record 416 in 1946<U+2013>47.<ref name=BOOK/><ref>{{Cite web| title = 55 Ed Koffenberger| work = Duke Blue Devils Basketball Statistical Database| publisher = Duke University Athletics Association| year = 2010| url = http://goduke.statsgeek.com/basketball-m/players/statlines.php?playerid=214| accessdate = September 16, 2010}}</ref>

Koffenberger was selected by the [[Golden State Warriors|Philadelphia Warriors]] in a late round of the [[1947 BAA Draft]], although he only briefly played professionally but never in the [[Basketball Association of America]].<ref name=GODUKE/><ref>{{Cite web| title = NBA Draft Picks From Duke University| work = basketball-reference.com| publisher = Sports Reference LLC| year = 2010| url = http://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/draft.cgi?college=duke| accessdate = September 16, 2010}}</ref> After basketball he became an engineer.<ref name=BOOK/>

He died of leukemia on September 21, 2014 at the age of 88.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Ex-Duke all-America Ed Koffenberger dies| work = heraldsun.com| url = http://www.heraldsun.com/sports/x711471529/Ex-Duke-all-America-Ed-Koffenberger-dies| accessdate = September 24, 2014}}</ref>

